# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andong-jjimdak
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] Cultivars of Korean zucchini include 'Seoulmadi', 'Bulam-sacheol', and 'Miso'.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] In Korean cuisine, the squash is used either fresh or dried.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] Fresh aehobak can be pan-fried, either julienned in batter into *buchimgae* or sliced and egg-washed as *jeon*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] It is often made into *namul*-*banchan* (seasoned vegetable side dish), usually seasoned with salted shrimp and stir-fried.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] Sometimes, aehobak features as the main ingredient in stew dishes such as *jijimi* and *mureum*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] Dried aehobak, called *hobak-goji*, can be prepared by slicing the squash thinly and sun-drying the slices.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] It is soaked before cooking, then usually stir-fried to make a *bokkeum* or *namul*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/aehobak] The squash is also used in royal court dishes such as *seon*, and more recently in *wolgwa-chae*, replacing the Oriental pickling melon.
[src:andong-jjimdak/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:andong-jjimdak/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:andong-jjimdak/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:andong-jjimdak/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] The dish is seasoned with hot chili pepper powder, doenjang, *ganjang* (soy sauce), minced garlic, and chopped scallions to make it spicy and hot.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] However, other ingredients such as *kongnamul* (soybean sprouts), *mideodeok* (미더덕, *Styela clava*), and *minari* (미나리, *Oenanthe javanica*) also play an important role in giving *agujjim* a refreshing and fragrant flavor.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] The fish is an excellent source of protein and has a rich taste as well as a palatable chewy texture.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] Its origins are known to be a fish market in the city of Masan, South Gyeongsang Province where local fishermen would ask cooks from the market eateries to create a tasty dish from the ugly fish.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] Until the 1940s, the fish was not eaten and was frequently discarded due to its ugly appearance and low commercial value.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] However, as fish began to become more scarce in the late 20th century, the newly found delicacy became popular.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] Seoul has two famous *agujjim* streets, in Sinsa-dong and the Jongno district.
[src:andong-jjimdak/agwi-jjim] The popular *jjim* dish is eaten with bowls of cooked rice, or sometimes restaurants will stir-fry the remaining sauce with rice and additional vegetables on the grill to make *Bokkeumbap* with a crispy charred crust.
[src:andong-jjimdak/airline-chicken] The name of the cut is variously attributed to the shape resembling an airplane wing or that, because the exposed bone could be used as a handle to pick up the entire piece and eat it out of hand, it made it easier to eat in-flight.
[src:andong-jjimdak/airline-chicken] The cut is also known as a *Frenched breast*, due to the end of the wing bone being trimmed or Frenched, or chicken supreme.
[src:andong-jjimdak/airline-chicken] It is also known as Statler chicken, a name that originated from the Statler Hotel Boston, built in 1927 by E.M.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock fillets are commonly packaged into block molds that are deep frozen and used throughout Europe and North America as raw material for high quality breaded and battered fish products.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Portions cut from frozen Alaska pollock fillet blocks are the most common choice for fast food restaurant fish sandwiches, for example in the McDonald's Filet-O-Fish.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock is also a common raw material used in the manufacture of surimi (fish paste).
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock is widely regarded as one of the best proteins for the manufacture of high quality surimi because of the high gel strength of its flesh.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Pollock has been consumed in Korea since the Joseon era (1392–1897).
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] In 1940, Alaska pollock was the most commonly caught fish in Korea, with more than 270,000 tonnes brought in from the Sea of Japan.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] However, the consumption of Alaska pollock in South Korea dropped to an estimated 260,000 tonnes per year by 2016.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Much of it is imported from Russia due to changes in sea water temperatures.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska Pollock is a sizeable resource of fish and makes up 32% of the total US landings and 58% of Alaska's.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Pollock is the target of many of the world's fisheries and represents about 5% of the world's harvest.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] In the United States water's alone over 1.5 million mt have been caught, giving an estimated value of 600- 900 million dollars in profit, between the years 1992–1996.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock fillets are layered into a block mold and deep-frozen for distribution.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] For high-quality products, high-grade fillets are frozen only once between catch and consumer.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] For lower quality, low-cost breaded and battered fish sticks, double-frozen or minced trim pieces are used instead.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock is commonly used in the fast food industry; in products such as McDonald's Filet-O-Fish sandwich Arby's Classic Fish sandwich, Long John Silver's Baja Fish Taco, and Birds Eye's Fish Fingers in Crispy Batter.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Trident Seafoods and Chuck Bundrant were instrumental in popularizing the fish in the US in the 1980s; prior to then it had been most popularly consumed in Asia.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock is considered the national fish of Korea.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Its Korean name, ***myeongtae*** (명태), has also spread to some neighbouring countries: It is called *mintay* (минтай) in Russia, and the roe is referred to as *mentai-ko* (明太子) in Japan, although the Japanese name for the fish itself is *suketōdara* (介党鱈).
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Every part of a *myeongtae*, including the intestines and the roe, is used in Korean cuisine.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] Alaska pollock roe, generally referred to simply as *pollock roe*, is a popular culinary ingredient in Japan, Korea, and Russia.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] In Korea, the roe is traditionally called *myeongnan* (명란) and the salted roe is called *myeongnan-jeot* (명란젓).
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] The roe was introduced to Japan after World War II, and is called *mentaiko* (明太子) in Japanese.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] The milder, less spicy version is called *tarako* (鱈子) in Japanese.
[src:andong-jjimdak/alaska-pollock-as-food] In Russia, Alaska pollock roe is sold as a canned product suspended in oil, which gives it a soft paste-like consistency.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] There are many speculations on the origin of the dish.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] One is that it is a specialty food of the inner rich village of Andong during the Joseon period, prepared and eaten for special occasions.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] Another assumption is that during the 1980s in the *Dak golmok* (닭골목, literally "chicken alley") of the "Andong Gu Market," restaurant owners there made a dish including ingredients that regulars demanded, which became the current *Andong-jjimdak*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] The most plausible speculation among existing assumptions is that merchants of the *Dak golmok* at the market created the dish to keep their position against the rapid expansion of Western fried chicken shops.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] Since *Andong-jjimdak* is cooked over high heat, it has less fat and can have various tastes by adding diverse ingredients according to recipe.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] It is popular among students and blue-collar workers due to the abundant portions compared to the price (generally around 20,000 won).
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] *Andong-jjimdak* is also considered a nutritious dish due to the high protein content from the chicken, and various vitamins provided by the vegetables in the dish.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] To make the dish, the broth is prepared first by boiling a cleaned chopped chicken, whole garlic, onions, ginger and a type of fresh green chili pepper called "Cheongyang gochu" (청양고추) altogether in a pot.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] The pepper is famous for its extreme spiciness and plays an important role in tasting the dish.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] The cooked chicken is simmered with a sauce made from *ganjang*, *mullyeot* (물엿, syrup-like condiment), sugar, and pepper in the broth.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] Slices of shiitake, and diced carrots, potatoes, and other vegetables are added in the pot and boiled over high heat for ten minutes.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] Whilst the carrots and potatoes are almost getting cooked, a little amount of wheat flour and spinach, sliced cucumber, scallions and the noodles are added to the pot as well.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong-jjimdak] After cooking, the dish is put on a plate and sesame seeds are spread over it.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Since the 1970s Andong has developed rapidly, although the population has fallen by nearly seventy thousand as people have moved away to Seoul, Busan, Daegu and other urban centres.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] In the late 1990s and early 2000s it became a tourism and cultural center.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong is known as a centre of culture and folk traditions.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The surrounding area maintains many types of traditions and the Andong Folk Festival is held in mid October every year.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] One of the most famous aspects of these cultural festivities are the Andong masks.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong National University, specialising in education and Korean folklore, has grown rapidly since the 1970s.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Other tertiary institutions include Andong Science College and Catholic Sangji College.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Around 1 BC, Andong was founded by the Jinhan people, and it was known as Gochang.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] During the Three Kingdoms period, the area was controlled by the Silla kingdom.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The Battle of Gochang in 930 was fought here between Hubaekje forces and the Goryeo army led by Wanggeon, who won control of the city and renamed it Andong.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] After the ascent of the Joseon dynasty to the throne of Korea, Andong became a centre of Confucianism.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The area was extremely conservative for a long time and produced many leading confucian scholars.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Toe-gye Yi Hwang (1501–1570), one of the most prominent of all Korean scholars, came from Andong.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Yi Hwang retired back to his homeland late in life and started the establishment of the great Confucian academy Dosan Seowon there, which was finished after his death.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] During this period Andong and its principal families were influential within Korean political circles, of which the three notable families were the Andong Kim, Andong Jang and Andong Kwon clans.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] After the 16th century Andong became less influential until the early 19th century, when a marriage of the local Kim family resulted in strong influence on the royal family.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong was the site of intense fighting during the Korean War in the early 1950s, the Battle of Andong.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Although the city was almost destroyed, it was quickly rebuilt.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] In 1976 the Andong Dam was built, providing the city with a reliable source of electricity.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] In 1999, Her Majesty the Queen Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom celebrated her 73rd birthday in the city.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] There is an exhibit dedicated to this historic visit at Hahoe folk village museum.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong soju is made using traditional methods that are centuries old unlike its popular modern counterparts.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] It is protected by government regulation to preserve authenticity and commands a steep premium in the marketplace.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong is divided into 1 eup, 13 myeon and 10 dong.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong has famous local foods that originated in the city such as *heotjesabap*, *Andong jjimdak*, *Andong soju* (a rice wine), *Andong sikhye* (a punch), *Geonjin guksu* (a noodle dish), and salted mackerel.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The nearest international airport is Daegu International Airport, located 92 kilometres (57 mi) south of Andong.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The Hahoe Folk Village is perhaps the most notable folk village in South Korea.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] This village is listed by the South Korean government with UNESCO as a World Heritage site with Yangdong Folk Village in 2010.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong is also a home of Confucian studies and academies during the Joseon period.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The notable examples of seowon, or Confucian academy are Dosan Seowon that enshrines Yi Hwang, Byeongsan Seowon for Yu Sŏngnyong, Imcheon Seowon for Kim Sŏngil, Gosan Seowon, Hwacheon Seowon and others.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Other notable visitor destinations are Sisadan, Jirye Artists' Colony, Bongjeongsa temple and Andong Icheondong Seokbulsang aka Jebiwon Stone Buddha.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] In the area where Andong Dam is located, there is a monument to the Andong Samil Movement to honor the March First Movement.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] In addition, there are Wonmom theme parks and Unbu parks.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Andong has a humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dwa*), but can be considered a borderline humid subtropical climate (Köppen: *Cwa*) using the −3 °C (27 °F) isotherm.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] The city is located in the mountainous region of central South Korea and is part of the temperate climate.
[src:andong-jjimdak/andong] Temperatures vary widely, fog is high at 79 days per year, seasonal winds are northwest in winter and northwest in summer.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] Certain types of foods consumed primarily as *anju* include *golbaengi muchim*, *nogari* with peanuts, and *jokbal*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] Until the Joseon period, alcohol was mainly served in *jumaks* (a type of inn or tavern), where soups with rice, along with traditional alcohol such as *makgeolli*, were served to guests.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] Since the introduction of beer and Western foods into Korea, mainly from Japan in the nineteenth century, bars and pubs have enjoyed a newfound popularity, and many types of Western foods have been consumed as *anju*.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] Some foods are considered to be best complemented by certain types of alcohol.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] For example, *samgyeopsal*, grilled pork belly, is considered to go best with *soju*, while fried chicken or Korean seasoned chicken goes well with beer.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] *Pajeon* and *makkeoli* (or *dongdongju*) is a popular combination for rainy days.
[src:andong-jjimdak/anju-food] There are a number of different types of bar in South Korea, and each category sells different kinds of food and alcoholic beverage.
